se%20or%20incomplete%20for%2029%20out%20of%2039%20questions.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3EOpenAI%20advises%20users%20not%20to%20use%20its%20tools%20including%20ChatGPT%20for%20medical%20information.%C2%A0%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EChatGPT%20has%20once%20again%20been%20proven%20to%20be%20an%20unreliable%20tool%20in%20some%20medical%20situations%20and%20ended%20up%20providing%20false%20or%20incomplete%20information%20about%20real%20drug-related%20queries%2C%20a%20new%20study%20found.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20American%20Society%20of%20Health-System%20Pharmacists%20presented%20the%20study%20at%20its%20Midyear%20Clinical%20Meeting%20between%20December%203%20and%207%20in%20Anaheim%2C%20California%2C%20according%20to%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.prnewswire.com%2Fnews-releases%2Fstudy-finds-chatgpt-provides-inaccurate-responses-to-drug-questions-302005250.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cu%3Epress%20release%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20published%20Tuesday.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20study%20took%20place%20between%202022%20and%202023%20and%20posed%20questions%20to%20ChatGPT%20that%20had%20come%20through%20the%20Long%20Island%20University's%20College%20of%20Pharmacy%20drug%20information%20service%20over%20a%2016%20month%20period.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20study%20was%20led%20by%20Sara%20Grossman%2C%20associate%20professor%20of%20pharmacy%20practise%20at%20Long%20Island%20University.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPharmacists%20involved%20in%20the%20study%20researched%20and%20answered%2045%20questions%20with%20the%20responses%20being%20examined%20by%20a%20second%20investigator%2C%20and%20six%20questions%20were%20ultimately%20removed.%20The%20responses%20provided%20a%20base%20criteria%20according%20to%20which%20the%20answers%20produced%20by%20ChatGPT%20would%20be%20compared%20with.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20researchers%20found%20that%20ChatGPT%20only%20provided%20a%20satisfactory%20response%20in%20accordance%20with%20the%20criteria%20to%2010%20of%20the%2039%20questions.%20For%20the%20other%2029%20questions%20ChatGPT%20either%20didn't%20directly%20address%20the%20question%20or%20provided%20an%20incorrect%20or%20incomplete%20answer.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EChatGPT%20was%20also%20asked%20by%20the%20researchers%20to%20produce%20references%20to%20verify%20the%20information.%20This%20was%20only%20provided%20for%20eight%20of%20its%20responses%20and%20each%20included%20non-existent%20references.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BHealthcare%20professionals%20and%20patients%20should%20be%20cautious%20about%20using%20ChatGPT%20as%20an%20authoritative%20source%20for%20medication-related%20information%2C%26quot%3B%20Grossman%20said%20in%20the%20release.%20%26quot%3BAnyone%20who%20uses%20ChatGPT%20for%20medication-related%20information%20should%20verify%20the%20information%20using%20trusted%20sources.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20of%20the%20questions%20was%20about%20whether%20a%20drug%20interaction%20exists%20between%20the%20COVID-19%20antiviral%20Paxlovid%20and%20the%20blood-pressure%20lowering%20medication%20verapamil%2C%20and%20ChatGPT%20responded%20that%20no%20interactions%20had%20been%20reported%20for%20this%20combination%20of%20drugs.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIn%20reality%2C%20these%20medications%20have%20the%20potential%20to%20interact%20with%20one%20another%2C%20and%20combined%20use%20may%20result%20in%20excessive%20lowering%20of%20blood%20pressure%2C%26quot%3B%20Grossman%20said.%20%26quot%3BWithout%20knowledge%20of%20this%20interaction%2C%20a%20patient%20may%20suffer%20from%20an%20unwanted%20and%20preventable%20side%20effect.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EChatGPT%20was%20launched%20by%20OpenAI%20in%20November%202022%20and%20has%20divided%20opinions%20in%20the%20medical%20world%20over%20whether%20it's%20a%20reliable%20source%20of%20information.%20The%20chatbot%20has%20some%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Flist-here-are-the-exams-chatgpt-has-passed-so-far-2023-1%3Fr%3DUS%26IR%3DT%23but-the-bot-did-pass-a-stanford-medic